ULA, Chuck or three-fingered pinch
description: Pinch grip with thumb and next two fingers (index and middle finger), MCPs flexed, DIPs and PIPs almost extended. Examples: Holding a pen or pencil.

name: ULA, Cylindrical grasp
description: All fingers flexed around the object, thumb wrapped around object in opposite direction. Examples: Holding a can, a brush handle, a hammer.

name: ULA, Spherical
description: All fingers and thumb adducted around an object, fingers more spread apart, palm often not involved. Examples: holding a ball, opening a jar, turning a doorknob, holding an apple, picking up a glass by its top.

name: ULA, Hook
description: Two or more fingers are wrapped around an object in a hook-like manner.Examples: Lifting a bucket with the handle, carrying purse or briefcase

name: ULA, Tip pinch (or tip to tip prehension)
description: Tip of the thumb has contact to the tip of another digit (most common it is the index), to pick up small objects. Examples: Pen, pin, coin
shortname: Tip pinch (or tip to tip prehension)

name: ULA, Lateral or key pinch
description: Pad of extended thumb is pressing an object against the radial side of the index. MCP and PIP of the fingers are flexed, thumb abducted and distal joints extended, bringing pads of the finger and thumb together.Examples: Card holding, turning a key, pulling a document out of an envelope etc.
